1. Business Understanding and Objective

Problem statement

Hospitals often face challenges in efficiently managing resources due to the varying length of stay (LOS) among patients.

This project aims to estimate the expected Length of Stay for new patients based on historical data of previous patients with known varying length of stay, using key hospital-related and patient-related indicators.

This Project will use different machine learning models to predict LOS. All of them will be evaluated, to define the best model for this project.

Business/clinical context

Accurant predictions of length of stay can help hospitals with:

Optimoptimization of treatment planning for patients, who have high risk of prolonged stays

Minimization of the varying length of stay in the hospital and improve efficiency in operational context

logistical management, which includes room and bed allocation

About dataset

Data that is used is original dataset from Topic3_healthcare_analytics_dataset.csv. It contains features related to patient, hospital and Length of stay for some patients on an individual case basis.

The target variable is 'Stay', which categorizes stay duration in 11 categories, which differ by the length of stay in days (e.g. 0-10, 11-20, ..., More than 100 days).

Each row in the raw data set represents a patient admission and therefore a unique case.

Main features in the dataset include Age, Type of Amission, Severity of Illness, Department, Ward Type, Ward facility code, Bed Grade, Available Extra Rooms in Hospital, Visitors with Patient, Admission Deposit, Hospital Code, and Hospital Type Code.

Main Objective

Our main objective is to train and evaluate a machine learning model that accurately predicts the patients' length of stays in the hospital, based on available data. This will help hospital management allocate resources, plan capacity, and improve patient health care outcomes.

Only Bed Grade and City_Code_Patient contain missing values, as well as the target Stay.

All three features are categorical in nature:

  • 'Bed Grade' is an ordinal variable representing the level or quality of hospital beds (14). Missing values will be filled with the mode.
  • 'City_Code_Patient' is a nominal variable representing patient city identifiers. Missing values will be filled with the mode to maintain the categorical balance of the dataset.
  • Stay represents the length of stay in 10 day intervals (1-10, 11-20,...,More than a 100 days). We will delete rows with missing Stay value when necessary to compute correlation with features and in the preprocessing steps before training our ML models.

Identifying and capping outliers in numerical variables

Before proceeding to correlation or modeling, it is important to identify potential outliers that could distort statistical relationships. We will focus on three numerical columns:

  • Available Extra Rooms in Hospital
  • Visitors with Patient
  • Admission_Deposit

Box plots will be used for visual inspection, and the interquartile range (IQR) method will be used to calculate statistical limits for each variable. These limits will help identify values that are extremely high or low compared to the majority.

In[15]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.boxplot(data=df_eda[numeric_columns], palette="Set2")
plt.title("Boxplot of Numerical Columns", fontsize=14)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Here we calculate IQR boundaries for each numeric column
for col in numeric_columns:
    Q1 = df_eda[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df_eda[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    if lower < 0:
        lower = 0

    outliers = df_eda[(df[col] < lower) | (df_eda[col] > upper)][col].count()
    print(f"{col}:")
    print(f" - Lower bound: {lower}")
    print(f" - Upper bound: {upper}")
    print(f" - Number of outliers: {outliers}\n")

Available Extra Rooms in Hospital:
 - Lower bound: 0
 - Upper bound: 7.0
 - Number of outliers: 1936

Visitors with Patient:
 - Lower bound: 0
 - Upper bound: 7.0
 - Number of outliers: 13884

Admission_Deposit:
 - Lower bound: 2352.5
 - Upper bound: 7236.5
 - Number of outliers: 17558

Available Extra Rooms in Hospital:

Most hospitals have up to 7 extra rooms available. A small number of hospitals report higher values, which may indicate larger facilities or data anomalies.

Visitors with Patient:

Most patients are accompanied by fewer than 7 visitors. However, a notable number of records exceed this threshold, possibly due to recording errors or exceptional cases.

Admission_Deposit:

The majority of admission deposits fall within this range between 2,352.5 and 7,236.5. Values above 7,236 may represent premium treatments or incorrect entries.

All three numerical variables: Available Extra Rooms in Hospital, Visitors with Patient, and Admission_Deposit, contain outliers that extend beyond the normal range defined by the IQR method.

However, these extreme values do not necessarily represent data entry errors. In a hospital context, unusually high numbers of visitors, available rooms, or deposit amounts can occur naturally due to differences in hospital size, service quality, or patient type. For this reason, we have decided not to remove or cap outliers.

# Define explicit orders for ordinal features
ordinal_orders = {
    'Bed Grade': [1, 2, 3, 4],  # example order
    'Severity of Illness': ['Minor', 'Moderate', 'Severe'],
    'Age': ['0-10', '11-20', '21-30', '31-40', '41-50', '51-60', '61-70', '71-80', '81-90', '91-100', 'More than 100'],
    'Stay': ['0-10', '11-20', '21-30', '31-40', '41-50', '51-60', '61-70', '71-80', '81-90', '91-100', 'More than 100 Days']
}

# Temporary encoding for EDA
df_encoded = df_eda.copy()

# Encode ordinal features
for col in ordinal_columns:
    if col in ordinal_orders:
        df_encoded[col] = pd.Categorical(df_encoded[col], categories=ordinal_orders[col], ordered=True).codes
    else:
        # fallback: convert to category codes
        df_encoded[col] = df_encoded[col].astype('category').cat.codes

# Encode nominal features
for col in nominal_columns:
    df_encoded[col] = df_encoded[col].astype('category').cat.codes

3.4 Correlation Analysis

Multicolinearity Check

In this section we perform multicollinearity check among the features to identify potentially redundant predictors.

Identifying such feature pairs is important for model building, as removing or combining highly correlated predictors can improve model stability and reduce multicollinearity issues.

In[61]:
# Select only numeric columns from the features list
# (dropping labels added for visualisation of categorical variables in previous sections)
corr_features = (
    df_encoded[features]
    .select_dtypes(include=['number'])
    .corr(method='pearson')
)

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
sns.heatmap(corr_features,
    annot=True,
    cmap='RdBu_r',
    center=0,
    fmt=".2f",
)
plt.title(
    "Correlation Heatmap (Numeric + Encoded Categorical Features)",
    fontsize=16,
    pad=15
)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In[62]:
# --- Detect highly correlated feature pairs ---
# Set correlation threshold
threshold = 0.8

# Get absolute values (since negative correlation also matters)
corr_matrix_abs = corr_features.abs()

# Create a mask to ignore self-correlations
upper_tri = corr_matrix_abs.where(
    np.triu(np.ones(corr_matrix_abs.shape), k=1).astype(bool)
)

# Find features with correlation greater than threshold
high_corr_pairs = [
    (col, row, upper_tri.loc[row, col])
    for col in upper_tri.columns
    for row in upper_tri.index
    if not pd.isna(upper_tri.loc[row, col]) and upper_tri.loc[row, col] > threshold
]

# Convert to DataFrame for easy viewing
high_corr_df = pd.DataFrame(high_corr_pairs, columns=['Feature_1', 'Feature_2', 'Correlation'])

print("Highly correlated feature pairs (|r| > {:.2f}):".format(threshold))
print(high_corr_df.sort_values(by='Correlation', ascending=False))

Highly correlated feature pairs (|r| > 0.80):
Empty DataFrame
Columns: [Feature_1, Feature_2, Correlation]
Index: []

There seems to be no significant correlation between features.

4. Data Cleaning & Preprocessing

We will now make the dataset ready for modeling. To do so, we will:

  • Handle missing values with imputation strategies
  • Remove or cap outliers
  • Encode categorical features
  • Split data into or train/val/test sets

4.1 Split Data into Test and Validation Sets

Feature Type Definition

First, we define the types of columns in the dataset distinguishing between quantitative (numerical) and qualitative (categorical) features. This helps us determine the appropriate preprocessing and encoding techniques for each type.

  1. Numerical Features (Quantitative)

These are features that represent measurable quantities values on a continuous or discrete numerical scale.

  1. Categorical Features (Qualitative)

These represent labels or groups rather than numeric quantities. They are further divided into subtypes:

  • Ordinal Features: Categorical features that have a natural order or ranking, but the intervals between categories are not necessarily equal.

  • Nominal Features with Low Cardinality: Categorical features with no intrinsic order and a small number of unique categories (here fewer than 10).

  • Nominal Features with High Cardinality: Categorical features with many unique categories (here more than 10).

A different strategy will be used for each of these feature/columns types (see section 4.3).

In[65]:
# Define numeric features
numeric_features = ['Available Extra Rooms in Hospital', 'Visitors with Patient', 'Admission_Deposit']

# Define all categorical features
categorical_features = [
    'Hospital_code', 'Hospital_type_code', 'City_Code_Hospital',
    'Hospital_region_code', 'Department', 'Ward_Type',

4.3 Features Preprocessing

Here we define our Pipelines for preprocessing. We have chosen the following strategies:

  1. Numeric features: Missing values in numerical feature columns are replaced with median, and the features are subsequently standardized to ensure consistent scaling and prevent distortion of model results

  2. Categorical features:

  • Ordinal features: Missing values are imputed with the mode, and the feature is ordinally encoded to preserve its natural order.
  • Low-cardinality nominal features: Missing values are imputed with the mode, and the feature is encoded using one-hot encoding.
  • High-cardinality nominal features: Missing values are imputed with the mode, and the feature is encoded using target encoding to avoid the curse of dimensionality, which can occur when one-hot encoding creates an excessively large dataset that is computationally expensive to process.
In[69]:
# --- Define transformers ---
numeric_transformer = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')), # Replace missing values with median
    ('scaler', StandardScaler()) # Standardize data
])

ordinal_transformer = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')), # Replace missing values with mode
    ('encoder', OrdinalEncoder()) # Apply ordinal encoding
])

low_card_transformer = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')), # Replace missing values with mode
    ('encoder', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse_output=False)) # Apply one-hot encoding
])

high_card_transformer = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')), # Replace missing values with mode
    ('encoder', TargetEncoder())  # # Apply target encoding, which requires y_train when fitting
])

# --- Combine transformers conditionally ---
transformers = [
    ('num', numeric_transformer, numeric_features), # Use numeric_transformer on numeric features
    ('ord', ordinal_transformer, ordinal_features) # Use ordinal_transformer on ordinal features
]

if low_card_features:
    transformers.append(('low_card_cat', low_card_transformer, low_card_features)) # Use low_card_transformer on low-cardinality nominal features
if high_card_features_names:
    transformers.append(('high_card_cat', high_card_transformer, high_card_features_names)) # Use high_card_transformer on high-cardinality nominal features

# Define Preprocessor
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(transformers=transformers)

5.2 Model Hyperparameter Tuning

Helper Functions to Evaluate Models

Model Evaluation Metrics

We selected accuracy as one of the metrics to evaluate model performance. Accuracy measures the fraction of exact matches between the predicted and true LOS values.

However, since our target is ordinal and multi-class, relying on accuracy alone can be misleading. In particular, small deviations from the true LOS are treated the same as large deviations, which can make the accuracy appear lower than the predictions are clinically meaningful.

To address this, we also use the following metrics:

  • Quadratic Weighted Kappa (QWK): Measures the agreement between predicted and true LOS while penalizing larger deviations more heavily. This makes it particularly suitable for ordinal targets, where the order of categories matters.

  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE): Computes the average absolute difference between predicted and true LOS, providing a measure of error in days, which is directly interpretable in a clinical context.

It is common for models with moderate accuracy (e.g., 0.40.5) to still achieve low MAE or high QWK, indicating that predictions are clinically useful even if not exactly correct.

Note: We do not use metrics such as RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) because they disproportionately penalize larger errors, which can exaggerate the perceived model inaccuracy in ordinal, multi-class settings and may not reflect clinical relevance as directly as MAE or QWK.

In[71]:
def evaluate_model(name, y_true, y_pred):
    """
    Evaluate the performance of a model on ordinal/categorical predictions.

    Parameters
    ----------
    name : str
        Name of the model (used for printing and result dictionary).
    y_true : array-like of shape (n_samples,)
        True labels of the target variable.
    y_pred : array-like of shape (n_samples,)
        Predicted labels by the model.

    Returns
    -------
    dict
        A dictionary containing the model name and key evaluation metrics:
        - "Accuracy": Fraction of exact matches between y_true and y_pred.
        - "QWK": Quadratic Weighted Kappa score, measures ordinal agreement.
        - "Ordinal_MAE": Mean absolute error between predicted and true ordinal labels.

    Side Effects
    ------------
    Prints:
        - Accuracy
        - Quadratic Weighted Kappa (QWK)
        - Ordinal MAE
    """
    acc = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
    qwk = cohen_kappa_score(y_true, y_pred, weights="quadratic")
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)

    print(f"\n=== {name} ===")
    print(f"Accuracy:        {acc:.4f}")
    print(f"Quadratic Kappa: {qwk:.4f}")
    print(f"Ordinal MAE:     {mae:.4f}")
    print("-" * 50)

    return {"Model": name, "Accuracy": acc,
            "QWK": qwk, "Ordinal_MAE": mae}

def qwk_scorer(y_true, y_pred):
    """Quadratic Weighted Kappa scoring function used to evaluate model performance during hyperparameter tuning"""
    return cohen_kappa_score(y_true, y_pred, weights="quadratic")

qwk_sklearn_scorer = make_scorer(qwk_scorer, greater_is_better=True)

Hyperparameter Tuning

In this section, we tune the hyperparameters of our models using Randomized Search with cross-validation (RandomizedSearchCV). This process involves sampling a fixed number of random combinations of hyperparameters (3 here) from a predefined search space (defined in hyperparameter grid) and evaluating each combination using cross-validation (3 folds here) to estimate its performance. By doing so, we can efficiently explore a range of parameter settings without exhaustively testing every possibility, which reduces computational cost compared to a full grid search while still identifying high-performing configurations.

We begin by defining a hyperparameter grid containing the set of model parameters to be considered for tuning.

In[72]:

In[73]:
# ---------------------- Hyperparameter tuning ----------------------

# Ensure target variables are integers
# Some ordinal models (e.g., OGBoost) require integer-encoded targets rather than categorical
y_train_encoded = y_train_encoded.astype(int)
y_val_encoded = y_val_encoded.astype(int)
y_test_encoded = y_test_encoded.astype(int)

# Dictionaries to store best models and cross-validation results
best_models = {}
cv_results = []

# Loop over all models defined in the `models` dictionary
for name, pipeline in models.items():
    print(f"\n--- Tuning {name} ---")

    # Retrieve the hyperparameter grid for the current model
    param_grid = param_grids.get(name, {})

    # Skip models that do not have a hyperparameter grid defined
    if not param_grid:
        print(f"No hyperparameter grid defined for {name}, skipping.")
        continue

    # Define RandomizedSearchCV for hyperparameter tuning
    search = RandomizedSearchCV(
        pipeline,                       # the ML pipeline (preprocessing + model)
        param_distributions=param_grid, # dictionary of hyperparameters to sample
        n_iter=10,                      # number of random parameter combinations to try
        scoring=qwk_sklearn_scorer,     # evaluation metric (here, Quadratic Weighted Kappa)
        cv=5,                           # number of folds for cross-validation
        verbose=1,                      # level of logging
        n_jobs=-1,                      # use all available cores for parallel processing
        random_state=42                 # ensures reproducible results
    )

    # Fit RandomizedSearchCV on the training data
    search.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

    # Store the best estimator found for this model
    best_models[name] = search.best_estimator_

    # Print the best hyperparameters and best CV score for this model
    print(f"Best params for {name}: {search.best_params_}")
    print(f"Best CV QWK for {name}: {search.best_score_:.4f}")

    # Evaluate the best model on the validation set
    y_pred_val = search.predict(X_val)
    metrics = evaluate_model(name, y_val_encoded, y_pred_val)

    # Append evaluation metrics to results list
    cv_results.append(metrics)

LightGBM is the best performing model, with the following results:

  • Accuracy: 0.4207
  • Quadratic Kappa: 0.6306
  • Ordinal MAE: 1.0660

This can be explained for the following reasons:

  1. Handles diverse data types with ease: It naturally works with numeric, ordinal, and categorical features without requiring complex preprocessing, this is different in Decision Trees or Random Forests, which need careful encoding. LightGBM can directly process categorical features.

  2. Takes advantage of gradient boosting: Boosting models like LightGBM build trees sequentially, which means they are correcting errors from previous ones and improve accuracy. This allows the model to capture non-linear relationships and subtle feature interactions that simpler models could miss.

  3. Performs well with large and complex feature sets: LightGBM can fficiently handle high-dimensional data, including features with many unique categories such as hospital codes or departments.

  4. Reduces overfitting risk: Thanks to early stopping and strong regularization techniques, LightGBM performs more reliably than a single Decision Tree.

  5. Flexible for ordinal and multi-class targets: LightGBM can be configured for regression, multi-class, or even ordinal regression tasks, making it adaptable to various problem types like predicting Length of Stay.

6. Feature Importance & Explainability

We will now examine feature importance to determine which factors most strongly influence the models predictions.

In[76]:
# --- Step 1: Access the preprocessor ---
preprocessor = best_model.named_steps['preprocess']

# --- Step 2: Extract all transformed feature names and mappings ---
feature_names = []
original_feature_map = []
mapping_table = {}

for name, transformer, cols in preprocessor.transformers_:
    # Handle pipelines (like numeric_transformer, low_card_transformer, etc.)
    if hasattr(transformer, 'get_feature_names_out'):
        names = transformer.get_feature_names_out(cols)
    elif hasattr(transformer, 'named_steps'):
        # Access final step in the pipeline
        last_step = list(transformer.named_steps.values())[-1]
        if hasattr(last_step, 'get_feature_names_out'):
            names = last_step.get_feature_names_out(cols)
        else:
            names = cols  # No feature expansion (e.g., TargetEncoder)
    else:
        names = cols  # passthrough or simple transformer

    # Extend total feature list
    feature_names.extend(names)

    # Ensure all names are strings and replace numeric names with original column name
    names = [str(n) if isinstance(n, str) else c for n in names]

    # Build mapping: original column  list of encoded feature names
    for c in cols:
        mapped = [n for n in names if n.startswith(c + "_")] or [c]
        mapping_table[c] = mapped

    # Build original feature map for each encoded feature
    for n in names:
        base_col = n.split('_')[0] if '_' in n else n
        original_feature_map.append(base_col)

# --- Step 3: Extract feature importances ---
if 'clf' in best_model.named_steps:
    importances = best_model.named_steps['clf'].feature_importances_
elif 'ord' in best_model.named_steps:  # for OGBoost
    importances = best_model.named_steps['ord'].feature_importances_
else:
    raise ValueError("Unknown estimator in pipeline")

# --- Step 4: Create detailed feature importance DataFrame ---
fi_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Encoded Feature': feature_names,
    'Original Feature': original_feature_map,
    'Importance': importances
}).sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)

# --- Step 5: Aggregate importances by original feature ---
grouped_fi = (
    fi_df.groupby('Original Feature')['Importance']
    .sum()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
    .reset_index()
)

# --- Step 6: Print mapping table (for inspection) ---
print(" Original  Encoded Feature Mapping:\n")
for orig, enc_list in mapping_table.items():

7. Conclusion & Recommendations

The best-performing model is LightGBM, achieving the following performance on the test set:

  • Accuracy: 0.4238
  • Quadratic Weighted Kappa (QWK): 0.6279
  • Ordinal Mean Absolute Error (MAE): 1.0652

Key drivers of Length of stay identified by the model include:

  • Department
  • Admission deposit
  • Visitors with patient
  • Ward
  • Age

These drivers make logical sense: patients with higher deposits or more visitors may correspond to different hospital types or care plans, and age naturally influences length of stay.

For future improvements, we recommend:

  • Further hyperparameter tuning, for example by increasing cross-validation folds, exploring more parameter combinations, or use grid/Bayesian search for optimal settings.
  • Feature engineering, for example by testing alternative imputation strategies, creating new derived features, or refining existing ones to enhance predictive power.
